<p>The <b>Heart of Perfect Wisdom Sutra</b> or <b>Heart Sutra</b> or <b>Essence of Wisdom Sutra</b> (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: प्रज्ञापारमिताहृदय <i>Prajñāpāramitā Hṛdaya</i>) (the word <i>sutra</i> is not present in known Sanskrit manuscripts<sup id="cite_ref-nattier200_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nattier200-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>) is a well-known <a href="/wiki/Mahayana" title="Mahayana">Mahāyāna</a> <a href="/wiki/Buddhist" title="Buddhist" class="mw-redirect">Buddhist</a> <a href="/wiki/Sutra" title="Sutra" class="mw-redirect">sutra</a> that is very popular among Mahayana Buddhists both for its brevity and depth of meaning. Some even claim that it is the best known<sup id="cite_ref-Pine_16_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pine_16-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> and most popular of all Buddhist scriptures.<sup id="cite_ref-Pine_18_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pine_18-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nattier153_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nattier153-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
